This is happening because, if the try statement at DriveSubsystem line 71 does not work, the config variable is not initialized to a value. I’m guessing you want the program to fully stop if the code in the try statement fails, so I would recommend just wrapping the whole AutoBuilder.configure() block in the try statement.

Hey!

We got Pathplanner working on our Maxswerve chassis mostly by copy/pasting from the Firebears 2846 github! This is basically always where I point people trying to get Pathplanner working with Maxswerve!

Specifically, the changes they made to their drive subsystem (which they call “Bass” - music themed!)

github.com

firebears-frc/FB2024/blob/main/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/Bass.java

package frc.robot.subsystems;

import org.littletonrobotics.junction.LoggedRobot;

import java.lang.annotation.Target;
import java.util.Optional;

import org.littletonrobotics.junction.AutoLogOutput;
import org.littletonrobotics.junction.Logger;

import com.kauailabs.navx.frc.AHRS;
import com.pathplanner.lib.util.ReplanningConfig;
import com.pathplanner.lib.util.PIDConstants;
import com.pathplanner.lib.util.PathPlannerLogging;
import com.pathplanner.lib.util.HolonomicPathFollowerConfig;
import com.pathplanner.lib.auto.AutoBuilder;
import com.pathplanner.lib.commands.PathPlannerAuto;

import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.DriverStation;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.SPI;
This file has been truncated. show original

Pay particular attention to the drive() and driveRobotRelative() methods they added, both of which (I believe) are named methods that Pathplanner requires in order to work. These are not in the stock code for MaxSwerve.

I would suggest copy/pasting the newly published MaxSwerve code, adding these two methods, along with the Autobuilder stuff should get you going!
